In nanotoxicology, numerous studies clearly demonstrate that multi-walled carbon nanotubes (MWCNT) and inhaled particulate matter (PM) induce lung injury (
 Kendall and Holgat, 2012; 
 Piperigkou et al., 2016) through acute and chronic inflammation, granuloma formation, and substantial interstitial lung fibrosis. MWCNT and PM can also exacerbate asthma-like conditions via innate pathways such as TLRs that trigger the generation of IL-25, IL-33, and thymic stromal lymphopoietin (TSLP). MWCNT also induce epithelial damage resulting in IL-33 release, which in turn promotes innate lymphoid cell recruitment and the development of IL-13-dependent inflammatory response (

  Beamer et al.
  , 2013

 ).
